<Layout title="Ophthalmology & ENT Assessment Tools" description="Ophthalmology and ENT assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Ophthalmology &amp; ENT</div>
  <h1>Ophthalmology &amp; ENT Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Bedside and clinical tools for visual acuity, pupillary response, and hearing assessment.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Snellen Chart</strong> — Standard visual acuity assessment at 20 feet (6 meters). Records visual acuity as fraction (20/20 = normal; 20/200 = legal blindness threshold in most jurisdictions).</li>
      <li><strong>Rosenbaum Pocket Vision Screener</strong> — Near vision card for bedside visual acuity testing; correlates with Snellen distance equivalents. Used when full Snellen chart testing is unavailable.</li>
      <li><strong>RAPD Assessment (Relative Afferent Pupillary Defect)</strong> — Swinging flashlight test detecting asymmetric optic nerve or retinal input. RAPD indicates unilateral or asymmetric optic pathway disease.</li>
      <li><strong>Tympanogram Interpretation</strong> — Acoustic immittance measurement classifying middle ear function: Type A (normal), Type As (stiffness), Type Ad (hypermobility), Type B (effusion/perforation), Type C (negative pressure).</li>
      <li><strong>Rinne Test</strong> — Tuning fork comparison of air conduction vs. bone conduction; normal (AC &gt; BC); conductive hearing loss (BC &gt; AC); sensorineural loss (AC &gt; BC but both reduced).</li>
      <li><strong>Weber Test</strong> — Tuning fork placed on vertex; sound lateralizes to affected ear in conductive loss; lateralizes to normal ear in sensorineural loss.</li>
      <li><strong>Hearing Handicap Inventory (HHI)</strong> — Self-report questionnaire measuring hearing loss impact on emotional and social function; guides referral for audiological evaluation and hearing aids.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
